---
layout: layout-base.njk
title: Best U.S. Northern Cities for Tomatoes | GrowByDate
description: Compare northern U.S. cities for outdoor tomato growing by heat margin, frost-free days, timing pressure, and variety flexibility.
canonical: "https://growbydate.com/data/rankings/best-us-northern-cities-for-tomatoes/"
datasetSchema:
  dateModified: "2026-06-13"
  spatialCoverage: "Northern United States"
  temporalCoverage: "Long-term climate planning normals"
  variableMeasured:
    - "Tomato growing suitability score"
    - "Frost-free season length"
    - "Growing degree day margin"
    - "Variety flexibility"
    - "City latitude"
  measurementTechnique: "Northern U.S. city ranking for outdoor tomato growing suitability using heat margin, frost-free days, timing pressure, and variety flexibility."
  keywords:
    - "best cities for tomatoes"
    - "northern tomato gardening"
    - "garden climate ranking"
    - "growing degree days"
    - "short-season gardening"
  distributionName: "Best U.S. Northern Cities For Tomatoes"
---

{% set board = bestUsNorthernCitiesForTomatoes %}
{% set top = board.top %}
{% set hardest = board.hardest %}

<section class="card leaderboardHero">
  <p class="eyebrow">Crop-city comparison</p>
  <h1>Best U.S. Northern Cities for Tomatoes</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    Tomatoes are possible in many northern gardens, but the easiest cities combine enough frost-free days with a strong heat margin after transplanting. This ranking compares northern U.S. cities by outdoor tomato fit, GDD margin, timing pressure, and variety flexibility.
  </p>

  <div class="leaderboardStatGrid" aria-label="Ranking summary">
    {% if top %}
      <div class="leaderboardStat">
        <span class="statLabel">Top city</span>
        <strong>{{ top.cityName }}</strong>
        <span>{{ top.score }}/100 · {{ top.label }}</span>
      </div>
    {% endif %}

    {% if hardest %}
      <div class="leaderboardStat">
        <span class="statLabel">Tightest fit</span>
        <strong>{{ hardest.cityName }}</strong>
        <span>{{ hardest.score }}/100 · {{ hardest.label }}</span>
      </div>
    {% endif %}

    <div class="leaderboardStat">
      <span class="statLabel">Cities compared</span>
      <strong>{{ board.entries.length }}</strong>
      <span>U.S. cities at or above {{ board.northernLatitudeCutoff }}°N</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>The ranking</h2>
  <p>
    Higher scores mean tomatoes have more outdoor breathing room in a typical season. Lower scores usually mean early varieties, timely indoor starts, warmer garden sites, or protection become more important.
  </p>

  <div class="tableWrap leaderboardTableWrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Rank</th>
          <th>Location</th>
          <th>Tomato fit</th>
          <th>GDD margin</th>
          <th>Frost-free days</th>
          <th>Best variety fit</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {% for row in board.entries %}
          <tr>
            <td><strong>#{{ row.rank }}</strong></td>
            <td>
              <a href="{{ row.url }}"><strong>{{ row.cityName }}</strong></a><br>
              <span class="small muted">{{ row.regionName }}, U.S. · {{ row.latitude }}°N</span>
            </td>
            <td>
              <strong>{{ row.score }}/100</strong><br>
              <span class="fitBadge fitBadge-{{ row.badgeClass }}">{{ row.label }}</span>
            </td>
            <td>
              {% if row.gddMargin >= 0 %}+{% endif %}{{ row.gddMargin }} GDD<br>
              <span class="small muted">{{ row.availableGddFromPlanting }} available / {{ row.targetGdd }} target</span>
            </td>
            <td>{{ row.frostFreeDays }}</td>
            <td>
              {% if row.fittingVarietyLabels.length %}
                {{ row.fittingVarietyLabels | join(", ") }}
              {% else %}
                No clear outdoor fit
              {% endif %}
            </td>
          </tr>
        {% endfor %}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="card leaderboardCallout">
  <h2>What this ranking means</h2>
  <p>
    This is a tomato climate-fit ranking, not a promise that every garden in a city will behave the same way. The strongest northern tomato cities usually have enough summer heat that gardeners can think about flavor, finish, and variety style instead of only chasing the fastest possible maturity date.
  </p>
  <p>
    For the raw climate side of the story, compare <a href="/data/rankings/us-cities-with-the-highest-growing-degree-days/">U.S. Cities With the Highest Growing Degree Days</a> and <a href="/data/rankings/us-cities-with-the-longest-growing-seasons/">U.S. Cities With the Longest Growing Seasons</a>.
  </p>
</section>

{% set sourceLinksVariant = "us-climate" %}
{% set sourceLinksId = "ranking-best-us-northern-cities-for-tomatoes" %}
{% set sourceLinksHeading = "Official source context for this ranking" %}
{% set sourceLinksIntro = "This ranking is a GrowByDate interpretation of frost, seasonal heat, crop margin, and timing signals. These links show the official source concepts behind the derived metrics." %}
{% include "components/external-source-links.njk" %}

<section class="card">
  <h2>Methodology</h2>
  <p>{{ board.methodology }}</p>
  <p>{{ board.caveat }}</p>
  <p class="small">
    Download: <a href="/assets/data/rankings/best-us-northern-cities-for-tomatoes.json">northern U.S. tomato comparison JSON</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "ItemList",
  "name": {{ board.title | dump | safe }},
  "description": {{ board.description | dump | safe }},
  "url": "https://growbydate.com/data/rankings/best-us-northern-cities-for-tomatoes/",
  "numberOfItems": {{ board.entries.length }},
  "itemListElement": [
    {% for row in board.entries %}
      {
        "@type": "ListItem",
        "position": {{ row.rank }},
        "name": {{ (row.cityName ~ " tomato fit score") | dump | safe }},
        "url": {{ (site.url ~ row.url) | dump | safe }}
      }{% if not loop.last %},{% endif %}
    {% endfor %}
  ]
}
</script>
